name: octylcyclopentane
source: American Petroleum Institute. Research Project 44; Selected Values of Properties of Hydrocarbons and Related Compounds. Texas A & M University; College Station; TX; 1973.
Reason: 1,3-dioxolane has a melting point of -106.0 degrees Celsius. The basic unit for comparison is cyclopentane, which has a melting point of -106.0 degrees Celsius. The introduction of eight octyl groups increases the molecular weight and van der Waals interactions, raising the melting point by approximately +80 degrees Celsius.
